{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-04-11T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A beach born from fire rarely does so subtly, yet Papagayo Beach manages exactly that. The shoreline we see today rests on the southern edge of Lanzarote, one of Spain's Canary Islands. Tropical fantasy? More like volcanic precision. Millions of years ago, this land rose in successive layers of basalt and ash thrust upward by submarine eruptions.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PlayaPapagayo_ROW1699824695_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PlayaPapagayo_ROW1699824695_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Papagayo Beach, Lanzarote, Canary Islands, Spain","Copyright":"© Gavin Hellier/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260411_PlayaPapagayo\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lanzarote+Canary+Islands+Spain&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260411_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260411_PlayaPapagayo"},"Ssd":"20260411","Name":"PlayaPapagayo","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1699824695","FullDateString":"11 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Ever caught siblings plotting? In Karula National Park, Estonia, it looks as though these two red fox kits froze mid-conspiracy, their expressions mirrored in curiosity and caution. They're not just springtime fluff; they're apprentices in survival. Born in litters averaging four to six kits, foxes grow quickly, their underground den becoming a wrestling ring, classroom and testing ground. Older kits often help feed, guard and teach the younger ones, turning play into practice and mischief into muscle memory.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.FoxSiblings_ROW1554598734_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.FoxSiblings_ROW1554598734_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Two young red foxes at Karula National Park, Estonia","Copyright":"© Sven Zacek/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260410_FoxSiblings\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Karula+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260410_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260410_FoxSiblings"},"Ssd":"20260410","Name":"FoxSiblings","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1554598734","FullDateString":"10 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Water spills in clean lines at Sgwd yr Eira, one of South Wales' most distinctive waterfalls. Its Welsh name means 'Waterfall of Snow,' referring to the pale curtain of water sliding over the rock face. What sets this waterfall apart is access. A narrow path leads visitors behind the falling water, immersing them in sound, light and movement at close range. Sgwd yr Eira lies within Bannau Brycheiniog National Park, often called 'Waterfall Country' for its network of rivers and falls carved into wooded gorges. Well-marked trails connect this waterfall to others along the River Hepste, making it a popular stop on longer hikes. Above the valleys, the landscape opens into rolling moorland and long ridgelines where upland paths are shaped by wind and changing weather. These contrasts define the Bannau Brycheiniog, where open, exposed uplands give way to sheltered water, tying the landscape together.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.WalesWaterfall_ROW4607856907_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.WalesWaterfall_ROW4607856907_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Sgwd yr Eira waterfall, Bannau Brycheiniog National Park, Wales","Copyright":"© Guy Edwardes/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260409_WalesWaterfall\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Bannau+Brycheiniog+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260409_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260409_WalesWaterfall"},"Ssd":"20260409","Name":"WalesWaterfall","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4607856907","FullDateString":"9 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Seattle's waterfront seems suspended between sea and sky as soft light settles on the horizon. The city is named after Chief Si'ahl, a leader of the Duwamish and Suquamish peoples, whose legacy remains important to the region's identity. Steep streets lead down to piers that sweep across Elliott Bay. Rising above the shoreline, the Space Needle stands out as the city's most recognisable landmark. Pike Place Market, founded in 1907, overlooks the waterfront and continues to anchor daily life and long-held traditions.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SeattleSunrise_ROW1229095485_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SeattleSunrise_ROW1229095485_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Seattle, Washington, United States","Copyright":"© Jim Patterson/Tandem Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260408_SeattleSunrise\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Seattle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260408_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260408_SeattleSunrise"},"Ssd":"20260408","Name":"SeattleSunrise","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1229095485","FullDateString":"8 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The beaver—buck-toothed, paddle-tailed and famously industrious—has been reshaping freshwater landscapes for millions of years. With their iron-reinforced orange incisors, these skilled rodents cut down trees and build dams that slow the flow of water, improve its quality and create wetlands that support a remarkable diversity of life. Their sturdy lodges, made of branches and mud, have underwater entrances that protect them from predators and keep their families safe.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BeaverPortrait_ROW1082400008_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BeaverPortrait_ROW1082400008_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Beaver, Germany","Copyright":"© Andyworks/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260407_BeaverPortrait\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Beaver+rodent&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260407_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260407_BeaverPortrait"},"Ssd":"20260407","Name":"BeaverPortrait","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1082400008","FullDateString":"7 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Picture northern Japan in the early 1600s. Castles stood at the crossroads of politics, trade and governance. Across generations, they came to reflect not only moments of tension but also endurance, adaptation and everyday life. Today's image features Hirosaki Castle, completed in 1611 under the Tsugaru clan, an influential Japanese samurai family. It was also known as Takaoka Castle. Fires, lightning strikes and strategic rebuilding reshaped parts of the complex, yet the castle continued to anchor local administration and culture throughout the Edo period. After the feudal system collapsed in the nineteenth century, its moats, gates and watchtowers survived as the grounds gradually became a public park famed for its thousands of cherry trees planted in the early twentieth century. Today the site remains a cultural landmark and one of Japan's most celebrated cherry‑blossom destinations.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CastleBlossoms_ROW0945099429_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CastleBlossoms_ROW0945099429_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Hirosaki Castle with cherry blossoms, Hirosaki, Japan","Copyright":"© Glenn Waters/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260406_CastleBlossoms\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Hirosaki+Castle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260406_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260406_CastleBlossoms"},"Ssd":"20260406","Name":"CastleBlossoms","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0945099429","FullDateString":"6 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Ever wondered what a high-mountain lake looks like before the hikers arrive? At over 1,940 metres above sea level, Lake Gentau sits quietly in the Pyrenees of south-west France, its cold waters reflecting granite slopes and shifting clouds. Reached on foot from the Ossau Valley, the lake has long been a pause point for shepherds and walkers crossing these summer pastures. Look up and you will spot the dark volcanic shape of Pic du Midi d'Ossau nearby. Why does that peak matter? For centuries it served as a natural landmark guiding travellers through the mountain passes between France and Spain. Today it sits near the western boundary of the Pyrenees National Park. On calm days the surface turns mirror-still, reflecting sky, rock and the sharp outline of the Ossau peak. Not a bad reward for a mountain walk.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LacGentau_ROW3338740451_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LacGentau_ROW3338740451_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Lake Gentau in the French Pyrenees, Pyrénées-Atlantiques, France","Copyright":"© MICHAUX Stéphane/Hemis.fr/Alamy","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260405_LacGentau\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lake+Gentau+French+Pyrenees&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260405_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260405_LacGentau"},"Ssd":"20260405","Name":"LacGentau","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3338740451","FullDateString":"5 apr. 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Rolling hills in Tuscany, Italy, feel like they've been styled with intent—soft curves, neat rows of vines and those tall, unmistakable cypress trees. Have you ever noticed how the landscape seems to change colour with the seasons? Spring brings bright greens and wildflowers, summer turns fields golden and autumn deepens everything into warm, earthy tones.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ToscanaSpring_ROW0859656735_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ToscanaSpring_ROW0859656735_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Rolling hills of Tuscany, Italy","Copyright":"© Andyworks/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260418_ToscanaSpring\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Tuscany+Italy&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260418_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260418_ToscanaSpring"},"Ssd":"20260418","Name":"ToscanaSpring","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0859656735","FullDateString":"18 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"When the sun sets, a mysterious animal takes over the skies: bats. With more than 1,400 species found on every continent except Antarctica, they play a vital role in keeping ecosystems in balance. They have existed for over 50 million years, and while only three species feed on blood, the vast majority rely on insects, fruit, nectar or pollen, helping to control pests and support plant life.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.FlyingFoxMom_ROW6773514789_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.FlyingFoxMom_ROW6773514789_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Grey-headed flying fox carrying her pup, Yarra Bend Park, Australia","Copyright":"© Doug Gimesy/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260417_FlyingFoxMom\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Grey-headed+flying+fox&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260417_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260417_FlyingFoxMom"},"Ssd":"20260417","Name":"FlyingFoxMom","Market":"ROW","Hash":"6773514789","FullDateString":"17 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Each spring, Skagit Valley in Washington, United States, transforms into a patchwork of colour that celebrates the arrival of bloom season. Throughout April, visitors explore tulip gardens and farmland lined with vibrant rows of flowers, all framed by mountain views. The valley's fertile soils, shaped by centuries of sediment from the Skagit River, make it one of the most productive agricultural regions in the Pacific Northwest. Tulips arrived here in the early twentieth century when farmers realised the cool springs and long daylight hours were ideal for growing bulbs.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SkagitTulips_ROW2420005352_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SkagitTulips_ROW2420005352_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Skagit Valley Tulip Fields, Washington, United States","Copyright":"© Alan Majchrowicz/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260416_SkagitTulips\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Skagit+Valley+Washington&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260416_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260416_SkagitTulips"},"Ssd":"20260416","Name":"SkagitTulips","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2420005352","FullDateString":"16 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Set in the foothills and front ranges of the Canadian Rockies, Kananaskis Country stretches across a vast network of protected valleys, dense forests and alpine peaks. Located in Alberta, the region was formally established in 1978, uniting several provincial parks and protected areas under a shared vision of conservation. Clear rivers cut through limestone cliffs, while spruce and pine forests rise toward high mountain passes.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.AlbertaSnowMts_ROW3394188074_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.AlbertaSnowMts_ROW3394188074_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Pine trees reflected in the Forgetmenot Pond in Kananaskis Country, Alberta, Canada","Copyright":"© chinaface/Getty images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260415_AlbertaSnowMts\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Kananaskis+Country+Alberta&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260415_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260415_AlbertaSnowMts"},"Ssd":"20260415","Name":"AlbertaSnowMts","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3394188074","FullDateString":"15 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Sea anemones may look like underwater flowers, but they're actually animals—close relatives of jellyfish and corals. Anchored to rocks or reefs, they use a sticky base and a crown of waving tentacles armed with tiny stingers to capture passing prey. Those stings can paralyse small fish, yet one famous neighbour is immune.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.OcellarisClownfish_ROW2121702907_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.OcellarisClownfish_ROW2121702907_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Common clownfish in a sea anemone, Raja Ampat Islands, Indonesia","Copyright":"© Magnus Lundgren/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260414_OcellarisClownfish\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Sea+anemone&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260414_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260414_OcellarisClownfish"},"Ssd":"20260414","Name":"OcellarisClownfish","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2121702907","FullDateString":"14 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"When the lights go down, the universe puts on a show. The image of the Milky Way glowing above Anza-Borrego Desert State Park captures that feeling perfectly. As California's largest state park and a certified International Dark-Sky Association Dark Sky Park, Anza-Borrego offers some of the clearest night skies in the country. On cloudless evenings, the heavens fill with planets, star clusters and the pale river of our home galaxy, a sight long lost to many city dwellers.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BorregoStars_ROW1985712263_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BorregoStars_ROW1985712263_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Milky Way over Anza-Borrego Desert State Park, California, United States","Copyright":"© Kevin Key/Slworking)/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260413_BorregoStars\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Anza+Borrego+Desert+State+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260413_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260413_BorregoStars"},"Ssd":"20260413","Name":"BorregoStars","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1985712263","FullDateString":"13 apr. 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Look up on a clear night and a bright moving star might actually be the International Space Station. That spirit of exploration lives on aboard the ISS, a laboratory where Earth never quite leaves the view. From the space station, astronauts photograph glowing city grids, curling auroras and lightning storms streaking through the atmosphere. The station orbits about 400 kilometres above Earth and circles the planet every 90 minutes, delivering up to 16 sunrises and sunsets each day.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SpaceTrails_ROW1837084616_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SpaceTrails_ROW1837084616_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"City lights streak below, taken from the International Space Station","Copyright":"© NASA","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260412_SpaceTrails\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=International+Space+Station&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260412_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260412_SpaceTrails"},"Ssd":"20260412","Name":"SpaceTrails","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1837084616","FullDateString":"12 apr. 2026"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD":"Dagens bild","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD_LEARN_MORE":"Mer information","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_DONATE_NOW":"Donera nu","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_FACT":"Snabbfakta:","LOC_HOMEPAGE_GALLERY_CARD_TITLE":"Nyligen använda startsidebilder","